:: action-approach-lancaster-farm {"position":"400,200","size":"150,100"}
You drive down the long, winding country road flanked by tall cornfields that rustle in the autumn breeze. The sky is a crisp blue, dotted with fluffy white clouds, and the sun casts a warm golden light over the landscape. As you approach the Lancaster Farm, the familiar sight of the two-story farmhouse comes into view, its white paint slightly weathered but still charming against the backdrop of rolling hills and dense forest. The old barn stands proudly nearby, its red paint faded but still vibrant, with hex signs adorning its facade. You can see the swimming pool nestled between the house and the forest, its water shimmering in the sunlight despite being abandoned. The corn maze is visible in the distance, a three-acre labyrinth that has become a local attraction during the fall season. You pull into the gravel driveway, the crunch of tires on stones breaking the serene silence of the countryside.

You note the farm has multiiple driveways, but you take the one that seems to lead to the house. There are a few cars in the driveway but no sign of activity. You can't tell if the lights are on. 


:: action-start-game-rules 
<<if $cardForJudge != "Bernadette">>\
    The card slides away from the center inlay. It is not the correct choice.
    [[Go back->loc-ouija-board]]
<<else>>\
<<set $chapter to "bern2" >>
As you place the card into the center inlay, it fuses with the board and all three inlays glow in a cycle, from left to right. First the "player" inlay, then the "arbitrator" inlay and finally the obscured "opponent".
You step back in both astonishment and fear and your body jolts to the sound of a something crashing into the house it self. Your head snaps toward the attic stairs but you are too surprised, too confused to run to see what has happened.
Now the house is silent again, except for a rythmic, repeating sound, the sound of footsteps. In your mind's eye, you can picture something moving through the living room, onto the kitchen tile and then up the stairs.
Instinctively, you hand falls to your sidearm.
The sounds continue, coming up the stairs and down the upstairs hallway and finally up the attic stairs. 

A dark figure enters the room, the dim light shows a black shawl, black boots and a strange black hat. But the face, her face, is pale and you recognize her, but not the look in her eye.
Bernadette looks in your direction but not at you, as if addressing an unseen audience. 
<<bern>>
The contest, the game is sealed.
I have accepted the role of arbitrator and my word is final as all parties have agreed.
I declare that all pawns, save one, have been lawfully and correctly moved out of play. Both sides will have the opportunity to petition me on the designation of the final pawn, however, in the interim I have decided to allow it the right of discovery, to unmask the opponent.
Behold, the assignment board is open.
<</bern>>
The room falls silent again.

You:
Draw your weapon.
Try to use your radio for backup.
Rush the figure in black. 
Ask a question 

Bernadette looks over at you and removes her hat. Then she nimbly drops to a sitting position, her legs crossed in front of her.
<<bern>>
    Hello again, Patrolman. I am sure you have questions, but it would be unfair of me to squander your remaining time with those. This is not a game between the people who live on this property, most of those are just pawns in the game, as, Unfortunately, you are as well.
    Do you understand what I mean by pawns? By opponent? By arbitrator?
<</bern>>
<<you>>Not really. Can you explain the rules of the game? What is going on here?<</you>>
<<bern>>
    I am the arbitrator, the judge. The game is  a contest, a wager of sorts between a powerful entity and a person who lives on this property - they are the opponent. They are your opponent as well as this is game that the pawns never win but as the last pawn you have an opportunity to void the game.
<</bern>>
<<you>>
    Why...why is a judge required? You say you are objective..
<</you>>
<<bern>>
    It is a fair question but you do not realize who is the player represented by the left card. You may guess if you wish but I will not confirm/deny. Let's say that mortals are wary to wage with that entity without an impartial judge to oversee the contest. I was called for this. 
<</bern>>
<<you>>
    What happens if the opponent wins?
<</you>>
<<bern>>
    They gain some power. I do not know those details. But in this case, the pawns are all sacrificed.
    <</bern>>
<<you>>And if the opponent loses?<</you>>
<<bern>>
    Then both the opponent and the pawns are sacrificed.
<</bern>>
<<you>>So it is a lose-lose situation?<</you>>
<<bern>>For the pawns, yes, most of them. The game is a wager but it is also a test of deception. The opponent has attempted to trick each pawn into agreeing to satisfy the vow dictated by the card they have accepted. In this case, the card was delivered to them under the guise of a Lenten oath rather than just explaining the card's true nature. I will admit that was clever but I am not yet satisfied and it is not clear that you have been deceived. You simply do not know, that is different.<</bern>>
<<you>>So what do I do now?<</you>>
<<bern>>The board is now open. You should match the photos of the pawns to the cards they havve been assigned. This is your only path to salvation. Ironically your correct assignment can help the opponent win.
    Do this first and we may speak again.
    <</bern>>
<<set $chapter to "gameboardopen1" >>
